    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "Hi,\r\n\r\nIf I have a function, say, \r\n```\r\ncdef double greater(double, double) nogil\r\n``` \r\nI can use it like this `f = greater` inside a nogil function and it works perfectly. However, if I make the function take fused types \r\n```\r\ncdef numeric greater(numeric, numeric) nogil\r\n```\r\nthen neither `f = greater` nor `f = greater[double]` works in a nogil function.\r\n\r\nI am just wondering if there is a workaround for this (or probably a more correct way to write it)?",
    "closed_at": "2020-03-27T01:14:15Z",
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "`f = greater` sounds like you've just found somewhere that Cython doesn't enforce it's GIL checks properly. You shouldn't be doing this. It'll fail dramatically and unexpectedly if `greater` does any manipulation of Python objects. Why not just make `greater` a `nogil` function?",
